</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1796,2022]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1436,152,298]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="55" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">The sculpture of the dorsal plates consists of irregular sized and shaped pores and, in some portion of the plates, also of large circular black dots; in some plates (some areas of the scapular plate, posterior portion of paired plates and median plates), the pores are arranged in a circular pattern around the black dots. On the central portion of the scapular plate and on the terminal plate also, very fine, almost invisible dots are present between the light pores.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,152,298]" pageId="6" pageNumber="55">
The species is probably cosmopolitan being recorded from all the zoogeographic regions, the Oriental and the Australian excluded. This is the first record of 
<taxonomicName box="[741,905,272,297]" class="Heterotardigrada" family="Echiniscidae" genus="Echiniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echiniscoidea" pageId="6" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="merokensis">
<emphasis box="[741,905,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="55">E. merokensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Azores.
</paragraph>
